noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 ended by showing that all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector spaces are isomorphic.
 That means, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{6}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{5}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{2\times3}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, and the vector space generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\{\sin t,\cos t,\sin2t,\cos2t,\sin3t,\cos3t\}$
\end_inset

 are all isomorphic.
 The essential ingredient of elements of each space is an ordered list of
 six real numbers.
 Their placement as coefficients or arrangement in a matrix can be tossed
 away without losing any information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Yet it might be nice to draw a distinction between odered lists of real
 numbers, polynomials, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times3$
\end_inset

 matrices, and linear combinations of the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 After all, they are different types of objects.
 Polynomials and elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are functions.
 A list of real numbers is just a list.
 A matrix is yet a different type of object.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One important feature of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 not included in the definition of a vector space is the dot product.
 We have seen that the dot product allows us to define the magnitudes and
 orthogonality of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 What if we could extend this idea to any vector space? We would need to
 write down the essential features of the dot product and hope that, as
 an abstract list of requirements, other vector spaces would admit similar
 operators.
 Representing elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 by column vectors, the dot product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u},\mathbf{v}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{T}\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Matrix-Multiplication"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 In other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}=u_{1},u_{2},\ldots,u_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=v_{1},v_{2},\ldots,v_{n}$
\end_inset

, then the dot product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, which we will begin to denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}=u_{1}v_{1}+u_{2}v_{2}+\cdots+u_{n}v_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{u} & =u_{1}u_{1}+u_{2}u_{2}+\cdots+u_{n}u_{n}\\
 & =u_{1}^{2}+u_{2}^{2}+\cdots+u_{n}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 is nonnegative (the squares of real numbers are nonnegative and the sum
 of nonegative numbers is nonnegative).
 This seems like an important property of the dot product since it is what
 led to using the dot product to define magnitude.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Length-and-Orthogonality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 it was shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{v}\bcdot\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 implying that the dot product is commutative.
 Commutativity is a fundamental property of addition and multiplication,
 so it seems like it is probably an important property of the dot product
 too.
 In fact, nonnegativity and commutativity are the only essential features
 of the dot product other than some sense of linearity, which follows from
 properties of real numbers.
 For the dot product of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{w})\bcdot\mathbf{v} & =\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w}\bcdot\mathbf{v}\\
 & \text{and}\\
(c\mathbf{u})\bcdot\mathbf{v} & =c(\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Can you show these identities are true? Answer on page 
