One reason for using the words norm and orthogonal instead of magnitude
 and perpendicular is because magnitude and perpendicular have ingrained
 geometric meaning that does not readily transer to objects such as matrices
 and functions (vectors in vector spaces other than 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

).
 What would it mean for two polynomials to be perpendicular, for example?
 Is there some geometric way to visualize this? Likely you are coming up
 short on an answer.
 No matter.
 If we can come up with an inner product on the vector space of polynomials,
 then orthogonality of two vectors (polynomials) is defined by the requirement
 that their inner product be zero.
